	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Cincinnati</placeName> <date>14 Oct 1858</date><add>&#63;</add></p>
				<p><addressee>Revd I Leeser</addressee></p>
				<p>Dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Having written to you<lb/> heretofore I consider it proper to<lb/> keep you posted in the <persName>Wise</persName> matters.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">As I told you he issued an<lb/> extra political sheet on <date>Monday</date><lb/> filled with the most absurd nonsense&#44;<lb/> and blackguardism.  Abusing me &#38;<lb/> all others who differed with him&#44;<lb/> inserting however this &#8220;If he &#40;<add>&#63;</add>&#41;<lb/> &#8220;will get one respectable man to<lb/> &#8220;sign his &#40;my&#41; card we will take<lb/> &#8220;back every word we said&#8221; Where<lb/> upon I procured the signature of<lb/> seven respectable men adopting<lb/> my card&#44; sent the same to him &#38;<lb/> told him he must either pronounce<lb/> those me not respectable or retract</p>
				<p rend="The following is written at the top of the page.">20&#45;402</p>
				<p rend=" The following is written in pencil near the top right of the page.">Saint <persName>Isaac<lb/> Mayer Wise</persName><lb/> <add>&#63;</add></p>
			<pb n="2R"/>
				<p>all he has said of me.  He replies<lb/> winces &#38; <sic>prevarecates</sic> &#38; asks me to<lb/> point out the portions of his paper<lb/> which give <sic>offence</sic> &#38; he will do so<lb/> as to mine &#38; three arbitrators shall<lb/> determine what shall be done by<lb/> either.  I demand his retraction<lb/> he again does not comply but fi<lb/>&#61;nally consents to leave the whole mat<lb/>ter to three persons which I have <add>a</add>greed<lb/> to do.  If it had not been for public<lb/> scandal a cowhide would have been<lb/> his merited chastisement&#44; as it is he<lb/> has lost caste amongst friend &#38; foe&#44;<lb/> all alike utterly denouncing his<lb/> course.  He has acted in a most<lb/> vile &#38; despicable manner&#44; first<lb/> in taking a bribe to support any<lb/> political party&#44; secondly in attemp<lb/><sic>x</sic>ting to carry out his views of poli<lb/>&#61;tics in a religious paper&#44; thirdly<lb/> his views were antagonist to &#190; of<lb/> his subscribers&#44; fourthly his</p>
			<pb n="3R"/>
				<p>scandalous abuse of men so eminently<lb/> his superior&#44; in every point of view<lb/> moral&#44; religious&#44; intellectual or in<lb/> any other way.  Without<lb/> knowing what if any political pre<lb/>ferences you may have&#44; you must<lb/> rejoice in the defeat &#38; total route<lb/> of him &#38; his party.  He has gone<lb/> today to <placeName>Louisville</placeName> will return on<lb/> <date>Tuesday</date> &#38; then will have to appear<lb/> before the three who I choose &#38; defend<lb/> himself against me.  You can<lb/> have no idea of the universal con<lb/>demnation he meets here among<lb/> all classes jews &#38; christians.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Did you receive his extras called<lb/> &#8220;Observers&#8221;.  If you wish to know<lb/> more address yours truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)"><persName role="author">Joseph Abraham</persName></p>
		</body>
